13. How does alcohol consumption vary among the surveyed individuals based on their country of birth?

s13 <- n1 %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(q14, countbirth) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(count = n()) |>
  drop_na() |>
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(countbirth) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(perc = count/sum(count)*100) %>%
  dplyr::select(countbirth, q14, count)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'q14'. You can override using the `.groups`
## argument.
drinking_by_country <- 
  s13 %>% 
  group_by(countbirth, q14) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(count = sum(count)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(countbirth) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(perc = count*100/sum(count),
                   q14 = q14) %>% 
  arrange(countbirth)

The intercept represents the estimated log-odds of being a smoker when all other predictors are zero. The coefficients for ageclass and q52 represent the estimated changes in log-odds of being a smoker associated with each level of the corresponding predictor, relative to the reference level.

The residual deviance measures the deviance of the fitted model from the observed data. A smaller residual deviance suggests a better fit. In this case, the residual deviance is 7199.

The AIC (Akaike Information Criterion) is a measure of model quality that penalizes complex models. In this case, the AIC value is 7209.

Overall, based on this logistic regression model, the coefficients provide estimates of the relationship between the predictors (ageclass and q52) and the log-odds of being a smoker. The negative coefficients for ageclass suggest a decreasing trend in the log-odds of being a smoker as age class increases. The positive coefficient for ageclass.C indicates a slightly increasing trend in the log-odds of being a smoker for the “C” age class compared to the reference level. The negative coefficient for q52.L suggests a decrease in the log-odds of being a smoker for the given level of q52 compared to the reference level.

The residual deviance is lower than the null deviance, indicating that the model provides a better fit to the data than the null model. However, the AIC value suggests that there may be room for improvement in the model’s predictive ability.

example_dat <- n1 %>%
  dplyr::select(q6, ageclass, q52) %>%
  drop_na(q6) %>%
  mutate(q6_binary = as.factor(q6),ageclass = as.factor(ageclass))

# Create a training and testing dataset
set.seed(123)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(example_dat$q6_binary, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- example_dat[trainIndex, ]
test_data <- example_dat[-trainIndex, ]

# Fit the logistic regression model
logistic_mod <- glm(q6_binary ~ ageclass + q52, data = train_data, family = "binomial")

# Evaluate the model on the test dataset

predicted_classes <- ifelse(predict(logistic_mod, newdata = test_data, type = "response") > 0.5, "Yes", "No")


# Convert test_data$q6_binary to a factor with the same levels as predicted_classes
test_data$q6_binary <- factor(test_data$q6_binary, levels = c("Yes", "No"))

# Convert predicted_classes to a factor with the same levels as test_data$q6_binary
predicted_classes <- factor(predicted_classes, levels = c("Yes", "No"))

# Create the confusion matrix
confusion_matrix <- confusionMatrix(predicted_classes, test_data$q6_binary)

accuracy <- round(confusion_matrix$overall["Accuracy"], digits = 4)


# Print the model summary, accuracy, and confusion matrix
summary(logistic_mod)
